"Seguin B., Arrouays D., Balesdent J., Soussana J.-F., Bondeau A., Smith P., Zaehle S., de Noblet N., Viovy N.","Moderating the impact of agriculture on climate",2007,"Agricultural and Forest Meteorology","142","2-4",,"278","287",,,10.1016/j.agrformet.2006.07.012,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33846435624&partnerID=40&md5=b666ea1e52a59d0295d2015c97176136","INRA, Unité Agroclim, Domaine Saint-Paul, Site Agroparc, F-84914 Avignon, France; INRA, Unité Infosol, Avenue de la Pomme de Pin, F-45166 Olivet, France; INRA, Unité Géochimie des sols et des eaux, Europôle méditerranéen de l'Arbois, BP 80, F-13545 Aix-en-Provence, France; INRA, Unité d'agronomie, 234 Av du Brézet, F- 63039 Clermont-Ferrand, France; Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research (PIK), D-14412 Potsdam, Germany; CEA-CNRS, LSCE, Bât. 701/ Orme des merisiers, F-91191 Gif-sur-Yvette Cedex, France","Seguin, B., INRA, Unité Agroclim, Domaine Saint-Paul, Site Agroparc, F-84914 Avignon, France; Arrouays, D., INRA, Unité Infosol, Avenue de la Pomme de Pin, F-45166 Olivet, France; Balesdent, J., INRA, Unité Géochimie des sols et des eaux, Europôle méditerranéen de l'Arbois, BP 80, F-13545 Aix-en-Provence, France; Soussana, J.-F., INRA, Unité d'agronomie, 234 Av du Brézet, F- 63039 Clermont-Ferrand, France; Bondeau, A., Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research (PIK), D-14412 Potsdam, Germany; Smith, P., Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research (PIK), D-14412 Potsdam, Germany, CEA-CNRS, LSCE, Bât. 701/ Orme des merisiers, F-91191 Gif-sur-Yvette Cedex, France; Zaehle, S., Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research (PIK), D-14412 Potsdam, Germany, CEA-CNRS, LSCE, Bât. 701/ Orme des merisiers, F-91191 Gif-sur-Yvette Cedex, France; de Noblet, N., CEA-CNRS, LSCE, Bât. 701/ Orme des merisiers, F-91191 Gif-sur-Yvette Cedex, France; Viovy, N., CEA-CNRS, LSCE, Bât. 701/ Orme des merisiers, F-91191 Gif-sur-Yvette Cedex, France","Many options are available for reducing the impact of agriculture on climate; however, it is difficult to provide a comprehensive set of solutions because several aspects are still poorly understood. An overall assessment of the various impacts of agriculture on climate is presented. It focuses on the trade-offs among the relevant greenhouse gases (GHG), CO2, N2O and CH4, and the geochemical and biophysical interactions between agriculture and climate. Three spatial scales are examined: field, farm, and regional scale. At the field level, both GHG and energy fluxes are related to technical decisions by the farmer. At the farm level, strategic decisions on the choice of production systems are governed by economical constraints. Land use and landscape govern the biophysical factors that act on the regional climate when spatially integrated. At the regional level, national and regional policies on GHG emissions and surface forcing influence global climate. The biochemical and geophysical contribution of agriculture to climate need to be considered using new approaches in terms of global warming. The use of GCMs appears to be an adequate tool at this scale for assessing the global effect on climate, upon which smaller-scale effects will be superimposed. © 2006 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Agriculture; Carbon cycle; Climate; Energy balance; Farm scale; Field scale; Global scale; Greenhouse gases; Water cycle","agricultural emission; biogeochemical cycle; climate change; climate effect; energy balance; environmental impact; global warming; greenhouse gas; risk assessment",,,,,,"Betts, R.A., Offset of the potential carbon sink from boreal forestation by decreases in surface albedo (2000) Nature, 408, pp. 187-189; Betts, R.A., Falloon, P., Biophysical forcing of climate by anthropogenic vegetation change (2007) Agric. For. Meteorol., 142, pp. 216-233; Boucher, O., Myhre, G., Myhre, A., Direct human influence of irrigation on atmospheric water vapour and climate (2004) Clim. Dynam., 22, pp. 597-603; Brovkin, V., Sitch, S., 